# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Use BFS starting from the `src` city and limiting the traversal to `k+1` levels. Keep track of the cost of the trip so far until every city on the way to the destination. If a city can be reached in multiple ways, remember the lowest cost option. We will either reach the `dst` city within `k+1` iterations or not. Return the correct answer accordingly.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N+E*k)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N+E*k)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
  public int findCheapestPrice(int n, int[][] flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
    List<int[]>[] adj = new ArrayList[n];

    for (var i=0; i<n; i++)
      adj[i] = new ArrayList<>();

    for (var flight : flights)
      adj[flight[0]].add(new int[] {flight[1], flight[2]});

    var costToCity = new int[n];
    Arrays.fill(costToCity, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

    var queue = new ArrayDeque<int[]>();
    queue.offer(new int[] {src, 0});

    while (k-- >= 0 && !queue.isEmpty()) {
      for (var i = queue.size(); i > 0; i--) {
        var stop = queue.poll();
        if (stop[1] >= costToCity[stop[0]])
          continue;

        costToCity[stop[0]] = stop[1];

        for (var flight : adj[stop[0]]) {
          if (flight[0] == dst)
            costToCity[dst] = Math.min(costToCity[dst], stop[1] + flight[1]);
          else
            queue.offer(new int[] {flight[0], stop[1] + flight[1]});
        }
      }
    }
    return costToCity[dst] == Integer.MAX_VALUE ? -1 : costToCity[dst];
  }
}
