# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We could use dijkstra here but the only problem seems to be appear is extra constraint of atmost k stops.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Let's suppose we are at a node before the destination node.So, can now be reach to the destination node from all the nodes just before destination node if we are able to reach atleast one of the these nodes. The answer is YES, because it's take only 1 stops from all such nodes. Can't we think opposite that we will go from the destination node to the neighbour node which is at least distance. If any of these node is able to reach to the source first. Then, that will be our answer. **So We will traverse the graph from destination to source not from the source to destination while applying dijkstra**
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O((number of edges)*log(number of nodes))
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(number of nodes+ number of edges)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        vector<pair<int, int>> adj[n];
        k=k+1;
        for(auto x: flights)
        {
            adj[x[1]].push_back({x[0], x[2]});
        }
        //{cost, {node, stops}}
        priority_queue<pair<int, pair<int, int>>, vector<pair<int, pair<int, int>>>, greater<pair<int, pair<int, int>>>> pendingNodes;
        vector<int> minCost(n, INT_MAX);
        pendingNodes.push({0, {dst, 0}});
        minCost[dst]=0;
        while(!pendingNodes.empty())
        {
            int cost=pendingNodes.top().first;
            int node=pendingNodes.top().second.first;
            int stops=pendingNodes.top().second.second;
            if(node==src)
            return cost;
            pendingNodes.pop();
            for(auto x: adj[node])
            {
if((cost+x.second)<minCost[x.first] && (stops+1)<=k)
{
minCost[x.first]=cost+x.second;
pendingNodes.push({minCost[x.first], {x.first, stops+1}});
}
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

