# 1. Brief explanation to relaxatioin
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/ec432558-bacf-44c2-a0bf-717ff557c03f_1643783358.1116207.jpeg)
For example, if we see a flight from city *i* to city *j* with price *p*, then the new minimal distance from source to *j* could be updated as shown in the formula below.
<img src="http://latex.codecogs.com/svg.image?dist[j] = min(dist[j], dist[i]+p)" title="form1" />

This is called relaxation in graph theory.


# 2. Suboptimal solution
This problem requires the solution to be within *k* stops, meaning that the path we find can not exceed *k+1* edges.
It means that while solving this problem, we might have to check some intermediate solutions that are not optimal.

Taking the image below, for example, assuming that the source city is 0 and destination city is 3;
When *k* equals 1, we might be stuck at city 2 whose optimal (minimal) distance is 2 with the number of stops as 2 if we do not consider the intermediate solution where the distance from the source is 5 with the number of stops as 1.
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/10cb4ad0-16ae-46ea-ad99-545c36940349_1643784894.322046.jpeg)


# 3. Bellman-Ford
In each iteration, we go through every edge in the vector *flights*.
In the other words, each iteration we are computing the smallest distance from each city to source city within *(number of iterations - 1)* stops.

Note that we could not update to the same distance vector or we may update a distance to a city multiple times in one iteration. (e.g. city *a* updates city *b*, and city *b* updates city *c* right after.)I
```
#define MAX_DIST 1e6 // greater than (n-1) edges * 1e4 (max price)

class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        vector<int> dist(n, MAX_DIST);
        vector<int> old_dist;

        dist[src] = 0;

        k++; // k stops -> k+1 iterations
        while(k--){
            old_dist.assign(dist.begin(), dist.end());
            for(auto& f: flights){
                dist[f[1]] = min(dist[f[1]], old_dist[f[0]] + f[2]);
            }
        }

        return (dist[dst] == MAX_DIST) ? -1 : dist[dst];
    }
};
```

# 4. Breadth-First Search
First of all, I prepare an adjacent list *adj*, where *adj[i]* is a unordered_map mapping the indices of cities where we can fly from city i to their respective prices of flights.

Then we perform a breadth-first search starting from the source city.
For each iteration, we are checking a set of cities that are *(number of iterations)* away from the source city.
```
#define MAX_DIST 1e6

class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
	    // adjacent list
        vector<unordered_map<int, int>> adj(n); // src: to->weight
        for(auto& f: flights)
            adj[f[0]][f[1]] = f[2];

        vector<int> dist(n, MAX_DIST);

        queue<vector<int>> q;
        q.push({src, 0});

        k++;
        while(k--){
            int q_size = q.size();
            while(q_size--){
                auto x = q.front(); q.pop();
                int cur_idx = x[0];
                int cur_dist = x[1];

                for(auto p: adj[cur_idx]){
                    int new_dist = p.second + cur_dist;
                    if(new_dist < dist[p.first]){
                        q.push({p.first, new_dist});
                        dist[p.first] = new_dist;
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        return (dist[dst] == MAX_DIST) ? -1 : dist[dst]; 
    }
};
```

# 5. Dijkstra
My implementation with Dijkastra is basically the same as the code in the solution.
Apart from that I move the line ```stop[new_idx] = new_stop;``` into the if scope doing relaxation.

The problem with the Dijkstra solution is that it will always go for the solution with the smallest distance regardless of the number of stops.
Therefore, I add a vector named *stop* recording the *number of stops* with the smallest distance for any city.
When there is an intermediate solution with a greater distance and a smaller *number of stops*, we will have to push it into priority_queue and check for possible better solutions for other cities.
```
#define MAX_DIST 1e6
#define vi vector<int>

class Solution {
private:
    class cmp {
    public:
        size_t operator()(const vi& v1, const vi& v2) const{ // {index, distance, stops}
            return v1[1] > v2[1]; // vector with smallest distance pop first
        }
    };
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        // adjacent list
        vector<unordered_map<int, int>> adj(n);
        for(auto f: flights)
            adj[f[0]][f[1]] = f[2];

        // dist vector
        vector<int> dist(n, MAX_DIST);

        // stop vector
        vector<int> stop(n, n);

        // priority queue for dijkstra
        priority_queue<vi, vector<vi>, cmp> pq;
        pq.push({src, 0, 0}); // src with 0 dist, 0 stops
        dist[src] = 0;
        stop[src] = 0;

        // dijkstra
        while(!pq.empty()){
            vi cur = pq.top(); pq.pop(); // pop smallest distance

            int cur_idx = cur[0];
            int cur_dist = cur[1];
            int cur_stop = cur[2];

            if(cur_idx == dst)
                return cur_dist;

            if(cur_stop == k + 1)
                continue;

            for(auto& p: adj[cur_idx]){
                int new_idx = p.first;
                int new_dist = cur_dist + p.second;
                int new_stop = cur_stop + 1;

                if(new_dist < dist[new_idx]){ // relaxation
                    dist[new_idx] = new_dist;
                    pq.push({new_idx, new_dist, new_stop});
                    stop[new_idx] = new_stop;
                }
                else if(new_stop < stop[new_idx]){
                    pq.push({new_idx, new_dist, new_stop});
                }
            }
        }

        return (dist[dst] == MAX_DIST) ? -1 : dist[dst];
    }
};
```

