solutions.content:
It's 2021 now, but most of the highest-voted posts were written in 2018/2019. They discussed about BFS, DFS, Dijkstra's, and Bellman-Ford. However, I find that (probably because LeetCode added more restrictive testcases), currenly only BFS and Bellman-Ford passes the test (I only verified this in C++). Nevertheless, in this post, we will discuss DFS, BFS, Dijkstra's and Bellman-Ford.



## BFS & DFS (TLE)

Walk for at most k steps from `src` and report the price if`dst` is reached. Note that:

- a node can be traversed more than once, as a path with more nodes can have shorter cost;
- Do early pruning by checking if `currPrice + price > minPrice`. This avoid infinite loops (but might traverse a loop multiple times).

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        // BFS
        unordered_map<int, vector<pair<int, int>>> F;
        for (vector<int>& f : flights)
            F[f[0]].push_back({f[1], f[2]});

        int minPrice = INT_MAX;
        queue<pair<int, int>> q({{src, 0}});
        for (int i = 0; i <= k+1 && !q.empty(); ++i) {
            int len = q.size();
            while (len-- > 0) {
                pair<int, int> p = q.front(); q.pop();
                int curr = p.first, currPrice = p.second;
                if (curr == dst) {
                    minPrice = min(minPrice, currPrice);
                    continue;
                }

                for (pair<int, int>& nextP : F[curr]) {
                    int next = nextP.first, price = nextP.second;

                    if (currPrice+price > minPrice) // pruning
                        continue;

                    minPrices[next] = currPrice+price;
                    q.push({next, price+currPrice});
                }
            }
        }
        return minPrice == INT_MAX ? -1 : minPrice;
    }
};
```



The DFS solution is almost the same, except that when backtracking, use `visited` to avoid loops (each loop traversed at most once).

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        // DFS
        unordered_map<int, vector<pair<int, int>>> F;
        for (vector<int>& f : flights)
            F[f[0]].push_back({f[1], f[2]});

        int res = INT_MAX;
        vector<int> visited(n, false);
        visited[src] = true;
        dfs(F, visited, src, dst, k+1, 0, res);
        return res == INT_MAX ? -1 : res;
    }

    void dfs(unordered_map<int, vector<pair<int, int>>>& F, vector<int>& visited, 
             int src, int dst, int k, int currPrice, int& res) {
        if (src == dst) {
            res = min(res, currPrice);
            return;
        }
        if (k == 0) {
            return;
        }

        for (auto p : F[src]) {
            auto [next, price] = p;
            if (visited[next] || currPrice+price > res) // pruning
                continue;

            visited[next] = true;
            dfs(F, visited, next, dst, k-1, currPrice+price, res);
            visited[next] = false;
        }
    }
};
```

However, both approaches above fail for TLE on LeetCode.





## BFS with more aggressive pruning (AC)

Can we prune more with BFS? Yes, `currPrice + price > minPrice` in the previous BFS solution might take several rounds in a loop before stopping, can we do better?

Yes. Whenever a node is traversed, remeber the min cost taken to reach the node. If the current cost at `u` is greater than the previous cost, then there's no point continuing. Here's the reason:

- In BFS, a later traversal to `u` means the current path is longer than previous path;
- It's possible for a later traversal (i.e., a path with more nodes on it) to have shorter cost, and this is the path we must consider;
- However, if a later traversal (i.e. a path with more nodes on it) has larger cost than previous path, just stop.

Based on this idea, we have the following code:

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        // BFS
        unordered_map<int, vector<pair<int, int>>> F;
        for (vector<int>& f : flights)
            F[f[0]].push_back({f[1], f[2]});

        unordered_map<int, int> minPrices; 
        int minPrice = INT_MAX;
        queue<pair<int, int>> q({{src, 0}});
        for (int i = 0; i <= k+1 && !q.empty(); ++i) {
            int len = q.size();
            while (len-- > 0) {
                pair<int, int> p = q.front(); q.pop();
                int curr = p.first, currPrice = p.second;
                if (curr == dst) {
                    minPrice = min(minPrice, currPrice);
                    continue;
                }

                for (pair<int, int>& nextP : F[curr]) {
                    int next = nextP.first, price = nextP.second;

                    // [Important] BFS early stop
                    // A node can be traversed more than once, because a path with more steps might have smaller cost;
                    // However, if a path with more steps have larger cost, there is no point continuing.
                    if (minPrices.count(next) > 0 && minPrices[next] < currPrice+price)
                        continue;

                    minPrices[next] = currPrice+price;
                    q.push({next, price+currPrice});
                }
            }
        }
        return minPrice == INT_MAX ? -1 : minPrice;
    }
}
```

It's not easy to implement the same idea with DFS: an earlier, unsuccessful traversal needs to clear the entries it filled in `minPrices`, but it's not straightforward to do that.



## Dijkstra's Algorithm (TLE)

Algorithm: [Wiki](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dijkstra%27s_algorithm)

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        // Dijkstra's algorithm
        typedef tuple<int,int,int> ti;

        unordered_map<int, vector<pair<int, int>>> F;
        for (vector<int>& f : flights)
            F[f[0]].push_back({f[1], f[2]});

        priority_queue<ti, vector<ti>, greater<ti>> pq; // <cost, node, steps>
        pq.push({0, src, k+1});
        while (!pq.empty()) {
            auto [currPrice, node, k] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
            if (node == dst) return currPrice;
            if (k == 0) continue;
            for (auto [next, price] : F[node]) {
                pq.push({currPrice+price, next, k-1});
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
```

The idea is similar to Dijkstra's algorithm. But note that we are not using `visited` to avoid revisiting a node, and not using `minDistances` to remeber the minimum distance to each node. Reason: the restriction of `k` stops. The final result might not be the shortest path - we might need to pick a path with fewer stops but higher cost.

Dijkstra's algorithm timeouts on LeetCode.

Detailed explanation on Dijkstra's algorithm implementation: [link](https://leetcode.com/problems/path-with-maximum-probability/discuss/732293/Dijkstra's-algorithm-implementation-C%2B%2B).



## Bellman-Ford (AC)

Algorithm: [Wiki](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bellman%E2%80%93Ford_algorithm)

```c++
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        // Bellman Ford
        vector<int> dp(n, INT_MAX);
        dp[src] = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < k+1; ++i) {
            vector<int> temp = dp;
            for (vector<int>& f : flights) {
                int u = f[0], v = f[1], price = f[2];
                if (temp[u] == INT_MAX) continue;
                dp[v] = min(dp[v], temp[u]+price); 
            }
        }
        return dp[dst] == INT_MAX ? -1 : dp[dst];
    }
};
```





## Note

The complexity of Dijkstra's algorithm is O(VlogV), while the complexity of Bellman-Ford is O(VE). Why Dijkstra's TLE but Bellman-Ford AC? Actually, we implement different from the original Dijkstra's, so the complexity is actually higher. 

