# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
BFS through the graph, keeping a state value of `(location, cost_so_far, stops_so_far)` in the queue.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Construct the `graph` for BFS. Specifically, for each node, we need to know all of its outgoing flights and how much they cost.
2. Instantiate a global array to track the `cheapest` means of arrival at each node.
3. At each iteration of BFS, disregard if the stops or cost are too high. Otherwise, update `cheapest` and add all the adjacent nodes to the queue.
    - Note: I initially set `stops = -1`. This is because `k` is being used to count the maximum number of layovers and arriving at your destination doesn't count. So, if `k = 0`, we want to make sure a single iteration of BFS is still run.    
4. Return the cost to get to `dst` if we were able to get there.

#### Disclaimer
@artemasoyan has a better [solution](https://leetcode.com/problems/cheapest-flights-within-k-stops/solutions/2877062/kotlin-belman-ford/) using the Bellman-Ford algorithm, which all the top submissions are copying. BFS here is a more standard approach, only ~20ms slower, and realistic to be expected in an interview. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(N + F*K)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N + F*K)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    fun findCheapestPrice(n: Int, flights: Array<IntArray>, src: Int, dst: Int, k: Int): Int {
        // Build graph
        val graph: Array<MutableList<IntArray>> = Array(n) { mutableListOf<IntArray>() }
        for ((from, to, cost) in flights) {
            graph[from].add(intArrayOf(to, cost))
        }

        // BFS
        var cheapest = IntArray(n) { Int.MAX_VALUE }
        var queue = LinkedList<IntArray>()
        queue.add(intArrayOf(src, 0, -1))
        while (queue.isNotEmpty()) {
            val (loc, cost, stops) = queue.poll()
            if (stops > k || cost >= cheapest[loc]) {
                continue
            }
            cheapest[loc] = cost
            for ((dest, price) in graph[loc]) {
                queue.add(intArrayOf(dest, cost + price, stops + 1))
            }
        }
        return if (cheapest[dst] == Int.MAX_VALUE) -1 else cheapest[dst]
    }
}
```

