solutions.content:
Idea behind Belloman ford algorithm:
	**If a vertex is `k` edges away from source, it's shortest path can found in `k` iterations (or Ralaxes).**

Algorithm:
`Instead N-1 iterate for k+1 (because for k stops there will be k+2 nodes in the path from src to dst).`

we took temp array in code to store distance because we only have to update distance of node if it is atmost i away.
Ex. let's say edegs 1->2 and 2->3
if we dont take temp array then in the first iteration itself distance of node 3 will get updated, As when 2->3 edge come distance of node 2 is already updated.


Please upvote if it helps!!

```
class Solution {
public:
    int findCheapestPrice(int n, vector<vector<int>>& flights, int src, int dst, int k) {
        vector<int> dist(n, INT_MAX);
        dist[src] = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<=k; i++) {
            vector<int> temp(dist);
            for(auto &e: flights) {
                int u = e[0], v = e[1], w = e[2];
                if(dist[u] != INT_MAX && temp[v] > dist[u] + w) temp[v] = dist[u] + w;
            }
            dist = temp;
        }
        //please upvote!
        return dist[dst] == INT_MAX ? -1 : dist[dst];
    }
};

```

